Who is child?
Any person under the age of 18 years is to be regarded as a child.
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-1]
What is pediatrics?
Pediatrics is the branch of medical science that deals with the medical care of the infants,
children, and adolescent. (Greek pais= child, iatros=healer)
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-1]
What do you mean by growth?
Physical maturation and signifies an increase in size of the body parts and various organs.
It occurs as a result of tissue hyperplasia, hypertrophy and differentiation.
What do you mean by development?
Acquisition & maturation of skills, behavior, and values on the part of the growing child.
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-14]
What are the factors affecting growth and development?
1. Genetic influence: e.g., tall parents have taller children
2. Nutrition
3. Low birth: LBW baby may grow at slower rate
4. Insulin: e.g., thyroxin, growth hormone, insulin etc.
5. Chronic illness: e.g., TB, heart disease, kidney disease etc.
6. Chromosomal abnormalities: e.g., down syndrome, turner’s syndrome
7. Emotional deprivation: e.g., children brought up in broken families may not grow and develop
normally
8. Others: e.g., social, cultural, and environmental factors
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-14]
What are the domains of Development?
1. Motor (Gross motor e.g., head control/ Fine motor e.g., drawing)
2. Cognitive (Construction of thought process e.g., problem solving)
3. Vision
4. Hearing
5. Speech
6. Social (e.g., child smiles to mother’s smile)
7. Emotional (e.g., love, anger)
8. Self-help /Autonomy (e.g., self-feeding, drinking)
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-19]
What are the principles of development?
1. A continuous process
2. Cephalocaudal in direction
3. Sequence of development is same, but the rate is different
4. Mass activities are replaced by specific responses
5. Primitive reflexes are lost before the appearance of corresponding voluntary movement
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-19]
What is IYCF?
The feeding program which includes both breast feeding as well as complementary feeding are
collectively known as infant and young child feeding (IYCF).
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-9]
What are the components of IYCF?
1. Promotion of early initiation of breast feeding (Within 1
st
hour of life)
2. Ensuring exclusive breast feeding for first 6 months of life
3. Proper complementary feeding from 6 months of age with continuation of breast feeding up to 2
years of age
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-9]
What are the advantages of Breast Feeding?
A. Benefits to the baby:
1. Complete food, species specific
2. Easily digested and well absorbed
3. Protects against infection
4. Promotes emotional bonding
5. Better brain growth and intelligence
6. Protects from allergy
B. Benefits to mother:
1. Helps in involution of uterus
2. Delays pregnancy
3. Lower risk of breast and ovarian cancer
4. Decreases mother's workload
C. Benefits to family & society:
1. Saves money
2. Promotes family planning
3. Decreases need for hospitalization
4. Contributes to child survival
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-10]
What are the immunologic benefits of breast feeding?
Mother’s mature milk contains enough antibodies which
1. Protects against infection
2. Protects from allergy
[MR Khan-5
th
-64]
What do you mean by Proper positioning and good attachment for breast feeding?
Proper positioning
Good attachment
The body is fully supported
The baby's chin is touching the breast
Body close to the mother
The baby's mouth is open widely
Straight head and body
The baby's lower lip is turned outwards
Facing breast, nose opposite to the nipple
More areola is seen above than below
[Prof. Abid Hossain Mollah-5

-10]
NEONATAL JAUNDICE
A 3 days neonate of 37 weeks of gestation weighing 2.5kg presented with yellow coloration of eyes
and skin for 2 days. What is your probable Dx?
Physiological jaundice
What are the sites of examinations of neonatal jaundice?
1. Whole body
2. Sclera
3. According to Kramer’s scale
[Ward Class of MMC]
How will you estimate serum bilirubin level with respect to dermal staining (Kramer’s scale)?
1. Face: 4-6 mg/dl
2. Chest and upper abdomen: 8-10 mg/dl
3. Lower abdomen and thigh: 12-14 mg/dl
4. Arms and lower legs: 15-18 mg/dl
5. Palm and sole: 15-20 mg/dl
[MR Khan-5
th
-49]
Why neonatal jaundice occurs?
1. Increased breakdown of RBC due to shortened life span (Fetal and neonatal 60-90 days,
pre-term 35-50 days)
2. Low hepatic excretory capacity (Due to impaired uptake of unconjugated bilirubin and
impaired conjugation of glucoronyl transferase)
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-78]
What are the causes of neonatal jaundice?
A. Jaundice appears within 1
st
24 hours of life:
1. Rh incompatibility, ABO incompatibility and Minor blood group incompatibility
2. G-6-PD deficiency
3. Congenital spherocytosis
B. On 2
nd
or 3
rd
day of life:
1. Physiological, usually
2. Crigler-Najjar syndrome
3. Breast-feeding jaundice (Due to increased enterohepatic circulation from less bowel
movement)
C. Between 3-7 days:
1. Jaundice of prematurity
2. Bacterial sepsis, UTI
3. Other infection: e.g., toxoplasma, CMV
D. After 1
st
week and persists beyond 2 weeks:
1. Unconjugated: Breast milk jaundice, hypothyroidism
2. Conjugated: e.g., sepsis, TORCH infection, biliary atresia etc.
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-78+Lecture of MMC]

[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-78]
What are the common nutritional disorders of Bangladesh?
1. Protein energy malnutrition (PEM)
2. Nutritional anaemia e.g., iron deficiency anaemia, vitamin B12 and folic acid deficiency etc.
3. Vitamin and other micronutrient deficiencies
4. Iodine deficiency disorders e.g., hypothyroidism

PROTEIN ENERGY MALNUTRITION (PEM)
A 2-year-old boy weighing 5.5 kg presented with severe wasting and bipedal oedema. What is
the most probable diagnosis?
Severe acute malnutrition (SAM)
What is PEM?
It is a pathological condition occurring most frequently in infant and young children due to long-
continued deficient intake of protein and calories.

PNEUMONIA
A 2-month baby comes to you with respiratory distress and cough. What is your DDs? What
investigation will you advice?
1. Acute bronchiolitis
2. Pneumonia
Investigations:
1. CBC
2. CXR
A 15-month-old boy presented with fever and cough for 4 days. On examination, he has fast
breathing and chest indrawing. Mention 2 possible differential diagnoses.
1. Pneumonia
2. Bronchiolitis
A 4-year-old child presented to pediatric ward with the complaints of fever, cough and
dyspnoea for 5 days. On examination, you found restricted chest movement and bronchial
breath sound on left side. What’s the Dx?
Pneumonia
What are the risk factors of pneumonia?
1. Severe malnutrition
2. Infectious diseases: e.g., measles, pertussis
3. Immune deficiency disorder: e.g., severe combined immune deficiency
4. Congenital lesions: e.g., ASD, VSD
5. Younger age: e.g., neonates and infant
6. Others: indoor air pollution and over crowding
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-110]
What are the roles of zinc?
1. Decreases duration, severity, and recurrence of disease
2. Immune modulator
3. Increases cellular growth and differentiation
4. Increase transport of electrolytes and water
5. Decreases cAMP mediated secretion by inhibiting K
+
channel in basolateral membrane
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-131]
Where will you manage a patient of some dehydration?
ORT corner
Where will you manage a patient of severe dehydration?
Hospital
What are the components of ORS?
1. Glucose: 13.6 g/L
2. NaCl: 2.6 g/L
3. Trisodium citrate: 2.9 g/L
4. KCl: 1.5 g/L
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-374]
What are the complications of diarrhoea?
1. Electrolyte imbalance: e.g., hypokalemia, metabolic acidosis, hyponatremia
2. Paralytic ileus
3. Acute renal failure
4. Growth failure/malnutrition
5. GBS
6. In dysentery: Rectal prolapse, dysentery
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-133]
02 years old child presented with acute watery diarrhoea for 16 days. O/E appearance-normal,
thirst- drinks normally. Classify according to IMCI.
Persistent diarrhoea with no dehydration
How will advise for diarrhoea?
1. Maintain hygiene
2. Drink clean tube well water
3. Avoid bottle/artificial feeding
4. Complete exclusive breast feeding and ensure appropriate weaning
5. Practice hand hygiene for both mother and child
[Ward class of MMC]
What are the causes of high rise of CSF protein?
1. TB meningitis
2. Spinal block (Tumor)
3. GBS
When CSF is hazy?
When neutrophil count in CSF is more than 250
[Lecture of MMC]
What are the EPI vaccines that can prevent meningitis?
1. BCG
2. Pneumococcal
3. Hemophilus Influenza type B (Penta)
[Lecture of MMC]

4. Poliomyelitis

1. Acute transverse myelitis (Initially, due to spinal shock)
2. GBS

BONE MARROW ASPIRATION NEEDLE
NEPHROTIC SYNDROME
Instruction: Please, study the supplied photograph of 4-year-old boy suffering from generalized
swelling of the body and scanty micturition for 1 week and answer the following questions.
What is your provisional Dx?
Nephrotic syndrome
What is the most common cause of this disease in children?
Minimal change disease
What are 2 other possibilities?
1. AGN
2. SAM
Mention 2 investigations with 2 expected findings.
1. Urine RME: Albuminuria, Granular and hyaline casts
2. 24 hours urinary total protein (UTP): 1g/m
2
/day or
3. Serum creatinine
4. Blood for C3, C4
5. Renal biopsy
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-241]
How will you treat nephrotic syndrome?
Counsel the parents about the nature of disease, treatment, and prognosis.
A. Specific: Prednisolone
B. Supportive:
1. Diet: Adequate in protein, No added salt
2. Fluid: Liberal fluid intake in mild oedema
3. Severe symptomatic oedema: Restrict sodium and fluid, oral frusemide and
spironolactone
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-241-42]
How will you follow up this patient (Nephrotic syndrome)?
1. In hospital: Vital signs e.g., pulse, BP, respiratory rate, weight, oedema, abdominal pain,
intake and output, bedside urine for albumin
2. After discharge: Albuminuria (To assess drug response)
3. Serum creatinine
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-242]
PLEURAL EFFUSION
Instruction: Study the Xray of 9-year-old boy who has been suffering from dyspnea for last few
years and answer the following questions.
What are the abnormal findings in this Xray?
1. Homogenous opacity in the right lower zone of both lungs
2. Crescentic upper border of opacity
3. Both costophrenic angles are obliterated
4. Both cardiophrenic angles are obliterated
What is your Dx?
Bilateral pleural effusion

1. NS
2. Cirrhosis of liver
3. CCF
4. Connective tissue disease

DIARRHOEA
A 09-month-old baby, weighing 8kg has been suffering from acute watery diarrhoea for 5 days.
You found the baby lethargic and drinking poorly on examination. Study the data and answer
the following questions.
What is the most likely Dx
Acute watery diarrhoea with severe dehydration
Which fluid will you prefer to manage this child?
Cholera saline / Ringer’s lactate solution
What will you the total amount of fluid?
100ml/kg, so 8X100= 800ml
What will be duration of rehydration of this baby?
Total 6 hours-
30ml/kg (240 ml) in 1 hour.
Then, 70ml/kg (560ml) in 5 hours.
What electrolyte imbalance may occur?
1. Hypokalemia
2. Hyponatremia
What are the common organisms of acute watery diarrhoea?
1. Rota virus, V. cholerae 01, 0139
2. E. coli (Enterotoxigenic, enteropathogenic and enteroadherent E. coli)
3. Campylobacter jejuni
4. Cryptosporidium
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-138]
What are the complications of diarrhoea?
1. Electrolyte imbalance: e.g., hypokalemia, metabolic acidosis, hyponatremia
2. Paralytic ileus
3. Acute renal failure
4. Growth failure/malnutrition
5. GBS
6. In dysentery: Rectal prolapse, dysentery
[Prof Abid Hossain Mollah-5
th
-133]
When will you reassess the patient?
After 4 hours and will reclassify for dehydration
